The diseases of globalization.
Globalization is put to the toughest test as never before.
Tensions simmer everywhere.
The majority of sub-Saharan Africa, South America, the Middle East, and Central Asia are stagnant or struggling with economic decline.
North America, Western Europe, and Japan are mired in slow growth and risk a new recession.
War now threatens in Iraq.
For proponents of open markets and free trade, this situation poses major challenges.
Why is globalization under such threat?
Why are its benefits apparently concentrated in a few places?
A more balanced globalization can it be implemented?
There is no simple answer to these questions.
Open markets are necessary for economic growth, but they barely suffice.
Certain regions of the world have reaped great benefits from globalization, particularly East Asia and China over the past few years.
Certain regions, however, have reaped meager benefits, particularly sub-Saharan Africa.
The U.S. government claims that poor countries are responsible for the majority of the problems they face.
The slow growth of Africa, claim U.S. leaders, is caused by the ineptitude of the African government.
However, life is more complicated than the Bush administration believes.
Consider the best-governed countries in Africa: Ghana, Tanzania, Malawi, The Gambia.
Each of them has experienced declining living standards over the past two decades, while a large number of Asian countries that ranked among the lowest in international comparisons of each country's governance (Pakistan, Bangladesh, Myanmar, and Sri Lanka) have experienced better economic growth.
It is true that economic performances are determined not only by governance standards, but also by geopolitics, geography, and economic structure.
Countries with high populations and therefore large internal markets tend to grow more quickly than countries with low populations.
Like all economic trends of this kind, there are counterexamples.
Coastal countries tend to be more performing than landlocked countries.
Countries with high levels of malaria tend to experience slower growth than countries with lower levels of malaria.
Countries in development that are proximate to rich markets, such as Mexico, tend to be more performing than countries that are far from major markets.
These differences hold great importance.
If wealthy countries pay little heed to these structural issues, the gaps between winners and losers will continue to widen.
If wealthy countries shift the blame to less fortunate countries by claiming they are in some way culturally or politically unable to benefit from globalization, we will not only create deeper pockets of poverty but also intensify unrest.
This, in turn, will lead to heightened levels of violence, hostile reactions, and terrorism.
It is therefore time for a more serious approach to globalization than that offered by wealthy countries, and particularly by America.
This approach must start with the most urgent task, namely addressing the basic needs of the world's poorest people.
In some cases, their sufferings can be alleviated primarily due to better governance within their country.
But in others, a honest look at the evidence gathered will reveal that the main causes of poverty concern diseases, climate instability, poor soils, distance from markets, etc.
A honest assessment would reveal that the poorest countries are unable to gather sufficient funds to address such issues on their own.
Rather than seeing rich countries giving more lectures on the poor governance of poor countries, real solutions require that rich countries offer sufficient financial assistance to overcome the most entrenched barriers.
An example will strikingly illustrate this situation.
The control of diseases requires a healthcare system capable of providing survival medications and basic preventive services such as bed nets to combat malaria and vitamins to combat nutritional deficiencies.
This healthcare system costs at least around $40 per person per year.
This amount represents only a grain of sand for rich countries that systematically spend more than $2,000 per person per year on healthcare, but it exceeds the means of poor countries like Malawi, which have annual incomes of $200 per person.
A functioning healthcare system would cost more than its government's entire revenue.
Even if Malawi is well governed, its population will die in large numbers due to diseases until it receives adequate assistance.
The success of globalization requires us to think more like doctors and less like preachers.
Rather than scolding the poor for their "sins", we must offer prudent diagnoses, as a good doctor would, for each country and each region, in order to understand the fundamental factors that hinder their economic growth and development.
In certain regions such as the Andes and Central Asia, the problem primarily stems from geographical isolation.
There, the task involves building roads, air links, and Internet connectivity to help remote regions establish productive links with the world.
Rich countries must contribute to the financing of these projects.
In sub-Saharan Africa, the main challenges lie in controlling diseases, soil fertility, and developing educational opportunities.
Once again, greater foreign assistance is required.
In other regions, the main issues revolve around water scarcity, discrimination against women or other groups, or a variety of specific problems.
It is now time to take the complexities inherent in globalization seriously.
The Washington Consensus' one-size-fits-all ideology is outdated.
At the brink of economic crisis, it is urgent to tackle the challenging task of making globalization benefit everyone.
We can achieve this if we remove the ideological blinders of the wealthy and mobilize a partnership between the rich and the poor.
Our shared future depends on it.
